{
  "text": "One reason for inconsistent results among studies comparing work capacity between the smokers and nonsmokers may be that some physiological variables determining VO 2 max are genetically determined [CITATION_1] and may interact with the smoking effects. In addition, it is well documented that smokers have tendencies to be less physically active than nonsmokers [CITATION_2] and tend to be heavier. Exercise responses between the smokers and nonsmokers should ideally be compared in subjects of similar age, exercise habits, body composition and VO 2 max in order to eliminate these influences, but these subject groups are difficult to assemble, resulting in few well-controlled studies where smoking is the only variable. The purpose of this study was to determine whether the habitual smoking altered responses to submaximal exercise. The comparison of the cardiorespiratory responses between two groups of generally similar and apparently healthy adult smokers and nonsmokers has been done during treadmill exercises ranging from low to high intensity.",
